Peel and grate the @garlic cloves{3}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}).

Pop a #medium saucepan{} (with a tight-fitting lid) on medium-high heat. Melt in
half the @butter{40%g}(divided). When hot, add the half of the garlic and stir-fry
for ~{1%minute}.

Pour the @water for the bulgur{240%ml} into the saucepan. Stir in half of the
@chicken stock paste{20%g}(divided) and bring to the boil.

Stir in the @bulgur wheat{120%g}, bring back up to the boil and simmer for
~{1%minute}. Pop a lid on the pan and remove from the heat. Leave to the side
for ~{12-15%minutes} or until ready to serve.

Meanwhile, heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a #large frying pan{} on medium-high heat.

Once the oil is hot, lay the @British chicken thighs{3%unit} flat in the pan.
Fry until the chicken is browned, ~{4-5%minutes} each side.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw chicken and its packaging.

Once the chicken is browned, add the @roasted spice and herb blend{1%sachet} and
remaining garlic into the pan. Fry for ~{1%minute}.

Pour the @tomato passata{1%carton} and @water for the sauce{150%ml} into the
#frying pan{}. Stir in the @sun-dried tomato paste{25%g}, remaining chicken stock
paste and @sugar{1%tsp}.

Bring to the boil, then lower the heat and simmer until the sauce has thickened
and the chicken is cooked through, ~{6-8%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: The chicken is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

When the bulgur wheat is ready, fluff it up with a #fork{}. Taste the bulgur
wheat and season with @salt{} and @pepper{} if needed.

When the chicken stew is cooked, add the @baby spinach{40%g} to the pan a handful
at a time until wilted and piping hot, ~{1-2%minutes}. Stir through the remaining
pantry butter. Taste the stew and season with @salt{} and @pepper{} if needed.

Share the bulgur wheat between #bowls{}.

Top with the chicken thighs and spoon over the sauce.

Crumble the @Greek style salad cheese{50%g} over the top to finish.

Enjoy!